Most English and Welsh wine does not come into the cheapest categories in the supermarkets. Some are quite expensive so it could be argued that it is the producers of cheap foreign wines which are the losers here and the consumers of those wines.In any case, the wine sellers and producers are likely to be on a hiding to nothing because the last thing the government will want at the moment would be the bad publicity which would ensue if they reduced the price of any of the cheaper types of alcoholic drink.Cider is an example of alcohol pricing which goes back a long way. Cider, mostly produced in England, used to be the cheapest way of consuming alcohol and the government altered the taxation banding many years ago with the deliberate intention of making the alcohol more expensive so that the alcohol price in cider would be roughly equivalent to beer. Of course, the industry responded by producing cheaper ciders so the unit alcohol price of cheap cider is still low.No point in complaining. The moral is that, if you want to support the exchequer, buy lots of cheap booze but if you want to support the industry, buy a smaller quantity of expensive booze. Of course, if you are rich, you can buy a large quantity of expensive booze and support both.



